Now we get to the part that actually makes or breaks an AML system.

You do not “pick” thresholds.
You derive them from expected loss + analyst capacity + regulatory tolerance.

The thresholds are the control mechanism that converts a probability model into an operational surveillance program.

We will do this properly (the way large banks and model-risk committees approve).

Step 0 — What you already have

Your classifier outputs a calibrated probability:

p=P(financial crime)
p=P(financial crime)

For every customer or case you now have:

0.01
0.07
0.18
0.34
0.52
0.81


Your job is to convert p → action

Action	Class
decline	ignore
unclear	analyst review
escalate	SAR/STR candidate

You need two thresholds:

Treview,  Tescalate
T
review
	​

,T
escalate
