Step 4 — Example numbers

Assume:

C_review = 80
C_false_escalate = 800
C_missed_crime = 80,000

Review threshold
Treview=80/80,000=0.001
T
review
	​

=80/80,000=0.001

(very low — meaning even tiny risk deserves a look in theory)

But operational capacity will override this (next step).

Escalate threshold
Tescalate=1−80/800=0.90
T
escalate
	​

=1−80/800=0.90

Meaning:
Only very strong evidence justifies SAR filing.

This is why escalation thresholds are always high.

Step 5 — Capacity constraint (the real-world adjustment)

Mathematics alone floods analysts.

So we apply queue control.

Procedure:

Score 6–12 months historical customers

Sort by probability (highest → lowest)

Simulate thresholds

Find probability where:

review alerts per day ≈ analyst team capacity


Example:

Threshold	Alerts/day
0.20	3200
0.30	1100
0.40	620
0.45	480

If analysts can handle 500/day:

Treview≈0.45
T
review
	​

≈0.45

Now you have an operationally feasible system.

Step 6 — Validate with PR curve (critical)

You now verify:

At chosen thresholds measure:

Metric	Why
Precision	SAR quality
Recall	crimes detected
False positive rate	workload

If precision collapses → escalation threshold too low
If recall collapses → escalation threshold too high

Step 7 — Final policy

You will end with something like:

p < 0.45          → Decline
0.45 ≤ p < 0.82   → Human review
p ≥ 0.82          → Escalate


These numbers are derived, not guessed.

Why regulators like this

Because you can defend:

thresholds based on economic reasoning

aligned with investigative capacity

consistent treatment of customers

documented model governance

You are no longer saying:

“We chose 0.5 because that’s standard.”

You are saying:

“We selected thresholds via expected-loss minimisation and operational capacity simulation.”

That is exactly the language model risk and compliance committees expect.
